SIMPLE: er
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Er
<hw>Er</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the chemical symbol for <er>erbium</er>,
a rare earth element. It has atomic number 68 and an atomic weight of
167.26.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> erbium.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-er</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: -er
<hw>-er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr><def>.</def> <sn>1.</sn> <ety>[AS.
<ets>-ere</ets>; akin to L. <ets>-arius</ets>.]</ety> <def>The
termination of many English words, denoting <xex>the agent</xex>; --
applied either to men or things; as in hat<xex>er</xex>,
farm<xex>er</xex>, heat<xex>er</xex>, grat<xex>er</xex>. At the end of
names of places, <xex>-er</xex> signifies <xex>a man of the place</xex>;
<as>as, London<ex>er</ex>, <it>i. e.</it>, London
<xex>man</xex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[AS. <ets>-ra</ets>; akin to G. <ets>-er</ets>,
Icel. <ets>-are</ets>, <ets>-re</ets>, Goth. <ets>-iza</ets>,
<ets>-<?/za</ets>, L. <ets>-ior</ets>, Gr. <?/, Skr.
<ets>-⟦imac⟧yas</ets>.]</ety> <def>A suffix used to form the comparative
degree of adjectives and adverbs; <as>as, warm<ex>er</ex>,
soon<ex>er</ex>, lat(e)<ex>er</ex>, earl(y)i<ex>er</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Era</ent>⟦br⟧
